---
/**
 * Experiment 005: L-Systems
 *
 * Interactive renderer for Lindenmayer Systems — grammar-based fractals that
 * model plant growth, snowflakes, and geometric self-similarity. A string is
 * rewritten by parallel substitution rules, then interpreted as turtle graphics
 * instructions to produce intricate fractal geometry.
 *
 * WHAT IS AN L-SYSTEM?
 * --------------------
 * Invented by botanist Aristid Lindenmayer in 1968 to model the branching
 * patterns of algae and plants. An L-system is a PARALLEL string rewriting
 * system:
 *
 *   1. Start with an AXIOM — a short seed string (e.g. "F--F--F")
 *   2. Apply PRODUCTION RULES simultaneously to every character
 *      (e.g. F → F+F--F+F means: replace every F with the new string)
 *   3. Repeat N times — the string grows exponentially
 *   4. Interpret the final string as TURTLE GRAPHICS commands
 *
 * The key word is "parallel": unlike sequential rewriting (Chomsky grammars),
 * ALL characters are replaced in one step. This models biological growth where
 * every cell divides simultaneously.
 *
 * WHY PLANTS GROW THIS WAY
 * ------------------------
 * Real plants exhibit self-similarity at multiple scales: a branch looks like
 * a smaller version of the whole tree, a fern frond looks like a smaller fern.
 * This isn't coincidence — it's optimal packing. By repeating the same growth
 * rule at every scale, plants maximize light capture and structural efficiency
 * with minimal genetic information. An L-system captures this: one simple rule,
 * applied recursively, produces complex organic form.
 *
 * WHAT IS TURTLE GRAPHICS?
 * ------------------------
 * Imagine a turtle on a canvas holding a pen. It understands simple commands:
 *   F — move forward one step (drawing a line)
 *   G — move forward one step (drawing a line, alternative symbol)
 *   + — turn left by the angle
 *   - — turn right by the angle
 *   [ — PUSH: save current position + angle onto a stack
 *   ] — POP: restore the last saved position + angle
 *
 * WHY [ AND ] ARE SO POWERFUL — BRANCHING VIA A STACK
 * ---------------------------------------------------
 * The bracket operators are what make L-systems capable of producing trees
 * and plants, not just space-filling curves. [ saves the turtle's state
 * (position + heading) onto a stack. ] restores the most recently saved
 * state. This creates BRANCHING: the turtle can explore one branch, pop
 * back to the fork, and explore another. Each nested [ increases the
 * "depth" — like nested function calls, the stack tracks where to return.
 *
 * Without brackets, the turtle can only trace a single continuous path.
 * With brackets, it can trace an entire tree.
 *
 * WHY ANGLE MATTERS SO MUCH
 * -------------------------
 * The SAME rule at DIFFERENT angles produces wildly different geometry.
 * F+F--F+F at 60° gives the Koch snowflake (triangular). At 90° it gives
 * a completely different space-filling pattern. Small angle changes (even
 * 1-2°) can shift a plant from bushy to spindly, or turn a curve from
 * open to self-intersecting. This is worth exploring — the angle slider
 * lets you see these transitions in real time.
 *
 * FRACTAL DIMENSION — BETWEEN 1D AND 2D
 * --------------------------------------
 * The Koch curve has a fractal dimension of log(4)/log(3) ≈ 1.26. What
 * does this mean intuitively? A straight line is 1D. A filled square is
 * 2D. The Koch curve is "more than a line" — it's infinitely long and
 * infinitely detailed — but "less than a surface" — it has zero area.
 * It lives between dimensions. Every iteration makes it longer (×4/3),
 * yet it fits in the same bounding triangle. More detail, same space.
 */
---

<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="utf-8" />
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1" />
  <title>005 — L-Systems | Generative Lab</title>
  <style>
    *, *::before, *::after { margin: 0; padding: 0; box-sizing: border-box; }

    body {
      background: #0a0a0f;
      color: #e0e0e0;
      font-family: 'SF Mono', 'Fira Code', 'Consolas', monospace;
      overflow: hidden;
      height: 100dvh;
      width: 100dvw;
    }

    #canvas-container {
      position: fixed;
      inset: 0;
      z-index: 0;
    }

    #controls {
      position: fixed;
      top: 16px;
      right: 16px;
      z-index: 10;
      background: rgba(10, 10, 15, 0.85);
      backdrop-filter: blur(12px);
      border: 1px solid rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.08);
      border-radius: 12px;
      padding: 20px;
      width: 280px;
      font-size: 12px;
      display: flex;
      flex-direction: column;
      gap: 12px;
      transition: opacity 0.3s;
      overflow: visible;
    }

    #controls.hidden {
      opacity: 0;
      pointer-events: none;
    }

    #controls h2 {
      font-size: 13px;
      font-weight: 600;
      letter-spacing: 0.05em;
      text-transform: uppercase;
      color: #888;
      margin-bottom: 4px;
    }

    .control-row {
      display: flex;
      justify-content: space-between;
      align-items: center;
      gap: 8px;
    }

    .control-row label {
      flex-shrink: 0;
      color: #aaa;
      min-width: 20px;
    }

    .control-row input[type="range"] {
      flex: 1;
      accent-color: #6a8cff;
    }

    .control-row .value {
      text-align: right;
      color: #6a8cff;
      font-variant-numeric: tabular-nums;
      white-space: nowrap;
      min-width: 36px;
      padding: 4px 12px 4px 8px;
      margin-right: -21px;
      background: rgba(10, 10, 15, 0.85);
      backdrop-filter: blur(12px);
      border: 1px solid rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.08);
      border-left: none;
      border-radius: 0 10px 10px 0;
      transform: translateX(0);
      transition: transform 0.35s cubic-bezier(0.34, 1.56, 0.64, 1);
    }

    .control-row .value.bulge {
      transform: translateX(12px);
    }

    .control-row select {
      flex: 1;
      background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.06);
      border: 1px solid rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.12);
      border-radius: 6px;
      color: #e0e0e0;
      padding: 4px 6px;
      font-family: inherit;
      font-size: 12px;
    }

    .button-row {
      display: flex;
      gap: 6px;
      flex-wrap: wrap;
    }

    .btn {
      background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.06);
      border: 1px solid rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.1);
      border-radius: 6px;
      color: #ccc;
      padding: 6px 10px;
      font-family: inherit;
      font-size: 11px;
      cursor: pointer;
      transition: background 0.15s;
    }

    .btn:hover { background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.12); }

    #toggle-ui {
      position: fixed;
      top: 16px;
      right: 312px;
      z-index: 11;
      background: rgba(10, 10, 15, 0.7);
      border: 1px solid rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.08);
      border-radius: 8px;
      color: #888;
      padding: 6px 10px;
      font-family: inherit;
      font-size: 12px;
      cursor: pointer;
    }

    #toggle-ui:hover { color: #ccc; }

    #back {
      position: fixed;
      top: 16px;
      left: 16px;
      z-index: 11;
      color: #555;
      text-decoration: none;
      font-family: inherit;
      font-size: 12px;
    }

    #back:hover { color: #aaa; }

    #status {
      font-size: 11px;
      color: #555;
      text-align: center;
    }

    .separator {
      height: 1px;
      background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.06);
      margin: 2px 0;
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <a id="back" href="/">← gallery</a>
  <button id="toggle-ui">UI</button>

  <div id="canvas-container"></div>

  <div id="controls">
    <h2>005 — L-Systems</h2>

    <div class="control-row">
      <label>preset</label>
      <select id="ctrl-preset">
        <option value="koch">Koch Snowflake</option>
        <option value="sierpinski">Sierpinski Triangle</option>
        <option value="dragon">Dragon Curve</option>
        <option value="plant" selected>Fractal Plant</option>
        <option value="fern">Barnsley Fern</option>
        <option value="pentigree">Pentigree</option>
      </select>
    </div>

    <div class="control-row">
      <label>iter</label>
      <input type="range" id="ctrl-iter" min="1" max="8" step="1" value="6" />
      <span class="value" id="val-iter">6</span>
    </div>

    <div class="control-row">
      <label>angle</label>
      <input type="range" id="ctrl-angle" min="-30" max="30" step="0.5" value="0" />
      <span class="value" id="val-angle">0°</span>
    </div>

    <div class="control-row">
      <label>length</label>
      <input type="range" id="ctrl-length" min="0.2" max="3" step="0.1" value="1" />
      <span class="value" id="val-length">1×</span>
    </div>

    <div class="separator"></div>

    <div class="control-row">
      <label>color</label>
      <select id="ctrl-color">
        <option value="single">single</option>
        <option value="depth" selected>depth</option>
        <option value="gradient">gradient</option>
      </select>
    </div>

    <div class="control-row">
      <label>bg</label>
      <select id="ctrl-bg">
        <option value="dark" selected>dark</option>
        <option value="light">light</option>
        <option value="paper">paper</option>
      </select>
    </div>

    <div class="separator"></div>

    <div class="button-row">
      <button class="btn" id="btn-save">save PNG</button>
    </div>

    <div id="status">ready</div>
  </div>

  <script>
    import { saveCanvasPNG } from '../shared/canvas.js';

    // -----------------------------------------------------------------------
    // L-SYSTEM PRESETS
    // -----------------------------------------------------------------------
    //
    // Each preset defines:
    //   axiom  — the starting string (the "seed")
    //   rules  — production rules: which character becomes which string
    //   angle  — the turning angle in degrees
    //   iter   — recommended number of iterations
    //
    // The axiom is typically short. After N iterations, the string grows
    // exponentially: if each F becomes 4 characters, after 6 iterations
    // a single F becomes 4^6 = 4096 characters. This exponential growth
    // is what produces fractal detail at every scale.
    // -----------------------------------------------------------------------

    const PRESETS = {
      koch: {
        name: 'Koch Snowflake',
        axiom: 'F--F--F',
        rules: { F: 'F+F--F+F' },
        angle: 60,
        iter: 4,
        // The Koch snowflake starts as an equilateral triangle (F--F--F with
        // 60° turns = three sides at 120° apart). Each side is replaced by
        // the Koch curve motif: go forward, turn 60° left, forward, turn 120°
        // right, forward, turn 60° left, forward. This adds a triangular bump
        // to each side. After infinite iterations, the perimeter is infinite
        // but the area is finite (bounded by a circle). Fractal dimension:
        // log(4)/log(3) ≈ 1.2619 — more than a line, less than a surface.
      },

      sierpinski: {
        name: 'Sierpinski Triangle',
        axiom: 'F-G-G',
        rules: { F: 'F-G+F+G-F', G: 'GG' },
        angle: 120,
        iter: 6,
        // The Sierpinski triangle is one of the simplest fractals: a triangle
        // with its center triangle removed, recursively. This L-system traces
        // it as a space-filling curve using two symbols F and G (both draw lines
        // but have different replacement rules). The 120° angle creates the
        // triangular geometry. Fractal dimension: log(3)/log(2) ≈ 1.585.
      },

      dragon: {
        name: 'Dragon Curve',
        axiom: 'FX',
        rules: { X: 'X+YF+', Y: '-FX-Y' },
        angle: 90,
        iter: 12,
        // The dragon curve was discovered by NASA physicists John Heighway,
        // Bruce Banks, and William Harter in 1966. You can create it physically
        // by folding a strip of paper in half repeatedly, then unfolding to 90°.
        // X and Y are "virtual" symbols — they control the structure but don't
        // draw anything themselves. Only F draws a line. The result is a
        // space-filling curve that tiles the plane: four copies arranged around
        // a point fill space with no gaps or overlaps.
      },

      plant: {
        name: 'Fractal Plant',
        axiom: 'X',
        rules: { X: 'F+[[X]-X]-F[-FX]+X', F: 'FF' },
        angle: 25,
        iter: 6,
        // This is the classic "weed" or bracketed OL-system. X is the growth
        // tip: it produces a stem (F), then branches left (+ [[X]) and right
        // (-X), creating a tree structure. F→FF doubles stem length each
        // iteration, making newer branches shorter than older ones — just like
        // real plants. The 25° angle produces a realistic branching pattern.
        //
        // CONNECTION TO REAL PLANT MORPHOLOGY:
        // Plants grow from meristems (growth tips) that can branch. Each
        // meristem follows the same genetic program. An L-system models this:
        // X = meristem, F = internode (stem segment), [/] = branching. The
        // result looks biological because it IS biological — this is literally
        // how plants encode their growth.
      },

      fern: {
        name: 'Barnsley Fern',
        axiom: 'X',
        rules: { X: 'F+[[X]-X]-F[-FX]+X', F: 'FF' },
        angle: 22.5,
        iter: 7,
        // Same rules as the fractal plant, but a tighter angle (22.5° vs 25°)
        // and one more iteration. This small change produces a denser, more
        // fern-like structure — demonstrating how sensitive L-systems are to
        // angle. In nature, different species use the same branching program
        // with slightly different angles, producing the diversity of leaf shapes
        // from a shared genetic toolkit.
      },

      pentigree: {
        name: 'Pentigree',
        axiom: 'F-F-F-F-F',
        rules: { F: 'F-F++F+F-F-F' },
        angle: 72,
        iter: 4,
        // Pentigree is a pentagonal fractal — the axiom draws a regular pentagon
        // (five sides, each separated by 72° = 360°/5). The replacement rule
        // adds a decorative bump to each edge, similar to Koch but with fivefold
        // symmetry. The result has the aesthetic of Islamic geometric art, with
        // intricate five-pointed star motifs at every scale.
      },
    };

    // -----------------------------------------------------------------------
    // L-SYSTEM STRING REWRITING ENGINE
    // -----------------------------------------------------------------------
    //
    // The rewriting step is conceptually simple but computationally important:
    // we scan the current string character by character and replace each one
    // according to the rules. Characters not in the rules pass through unchanged.
    //
    // PARALLEL vs SEQUENTIAL: In a Chomsky grammar (like most programming
    // languages), rules are applied one at a time. In an L-system, ALL
    // characters are replaced simultaneously in one pass. This models biological
    // growth: every cell divides at once, not one after another.
    //
    // The string grows exponentially. If a rule maps one character to K
    // characters, after N iterations you have ~K^N characters. For the Koch
    // curve (K=4, N=6), that's 4^6 = 4096 segments. We cap iterations to
    // prevent the browser from choking on multi-million character strings.
    // -----------------------------------------------------------------------

    function rewrite(axiom, rules, iterations, maxLen = Infinity) {
      let current = axiom;
      for (let i = 0; i < iterations; i++) {
        let next = '';
        for (const ch of current) {
          next += rules[ch] ?? ch;
          if (next.length > maxLen) return null; // too large, bail
        }
        current = next;
      }
      return current;
    }

    // -----------------------------------------------------------------------
    // TURTLE GRAPHICS INTERPRETER
    // -----------------------------------------------------------------------
    //
    // The turtle walks the string, maintaining its state:
    //   (x, y)   — position on the canvas
    //   angle    — heading in radians (0 = pointing right)
    //   depth    — current stack depth (how many [ are open)
    //
    // Commands:
    //   F, G  — move forward by `stepLen`, recording the line segment
    //   +     — turn left (counter-clockwise) by the angle
    //   -     — turn right (clockwise) by the angle
    //   [     — PUSH state onto stack (save position + heading for later)
    //   ]     — POP state from stack (return to saved position + heading)
    //
    // THE STACK IS THE KEY TO BRANCHING:
    // When the turtle hits [, it saves its current position and heading.
    // It then explores a branch. When it hits ], it teleports back to the
    // saved state and can start a new branch from the same fork point.
    // Nested brackets create sub-branches — the stack tracks the full
    // return path. This is identical to how function call stacks work in
    // programming: [ = function call, ] = return.
    //
    // We do TWO passes:
    //   Pass 1: compute the bounding box of all segments (no drawing)
    //   Pass 2: draw with a transform that centers and scales to fit the canvas
    // -----------------------------------------------------------------------

    function interpretToSegments(str, angleDeg, stepLen) {
      const angleRad = angleDeg * Math.PI / 180;
      const segments = [];
      let x = 0, y = 0, heading = -Math.PI / 2; // Start pointing up
      let depth = 0;
      let maxDepth = 0;
      const stack = [];

      for (const ch of str) {
        switch (ch) {
          case 'F':
          case 'G': {
            // Move forward, recording the line segment with its stack depth
            const nx = x + Math.cos(heading) * stepLen;
            const ny = y + Math.sin(heading) * stepLen;
            segments.push({ x1: x, y1: y, x2: nx, y2: ny, depth });
            x = nx;
            y = ny;
            break;
          }
          case '+':
            // Turn left (counter-clockwise) — subtract angle because
            // screen Y is inverted, but we handle that in the transform
            heading -= angleRad;
            break;
          case '-':
            // Turn right (clockwise)
            heading += angleRad;
            break;
          case '[':
            // PUSH — save the turtle's state so we can return here later.
            // This is the "fork" point of a branch. Everything between this
            // [ and its matching ] is a sub-branch that the turtle explores
            // and then backtracks from.
            stack.push({ x, y, heading, depth });
            depth++;
            if (depth > maxDepth) maxDepth = depth;
            break;
          case ']':
            // POP — restore the last saved state. The turtle "teleports" back
            // to the fork point, ready to start a new branch. The stack ensures
            // correct nesting: the most recent [ is always restored first (LIFO).
            if (stack.length > 0) {
              const saved = stack.pop();
              x = saved.x;
              y = saved.y;
              heading = saved.heading;
              depth = saved.depth;
            }
            break;
          // Characters like X, Y that have no drawing command are ignored.
          // They exist only to control the string rewriting — they're
          // "structural" symbols that shape the grammar but produce no
          // visible output.
        }
      }

      return { segments, maxDepth };
    }

    // -----------------------------------------------------------------------
    // BOUNDING BOX AND AUTO-SCALING
    // -----------------------------------------------------------------------
    //
    // L-systems can produce geometry at any position and scale depending on
    // the axiom, rules, angle, and iterations. To display them nicely, we
    // compute the bounding box of all segments, then apply a transform that
    // centers and scales the result to fit the canvas with padding.
    // -----------------------------------------------------------------------

    function computeBounds(segments) {
      let xMin = Infinity, xMax = -Infinity;
      let yMin = Infinity, yMax = -Infinity;

      for (const s of segments) {
        if (s.x1 < xMin) xMin = s.x1;
        if (s.x1 > xMax) xMax = s.x1;
        if (s.y1 < yMin) yMin = s.y1;
        if (s.y1 > yMax) yMax = s.y1;
        if (s.x2 < xMin) xMin = s.x2;
        if (s.x2 > xMax) xMax = s.x2;
        if (s.y2 < yMin) yMin = s.y2;
        if (s.y2 > yMax) yMax = s.y2;
      }

      return { xMin, xMax, yMin, yMax };
    }

    // -----------------------------------------------------------------------
    // Canvas setup
    // -----------------------------------------------------------------------
    const container = document.getElementById('canvas-container');
    const canvas = document.createElement('canvas');
    canvas.style.cssText = 'display:block;width:100%;height:100%;';
    container.appendChild(canvas);
    const ctx = canvas.getContext('2d');

    let W = 0, H = 0;

    function resize() {
      W = container.clientWidth;
      H = container.clientHeight;
      canvas.width = W;
      canvas.height = H;
    }

    resize();

    // -----------------------------------------------------------------------
    // Background definitions
    // -----------------------------------------------------------------------
    const BACKGROUNDS = {
      dark:  { fill: '#0a0a0f', defaultStroke: '#c8d4ff' },
      light: { fill: '#f5f2eb', defaultStroke: '#2a2a3a' },
      paper: { fill: '#e8dfc8', defaultStroke: '#3a3020' },
    };

    // -----------------------------------------------------------------------
    // Color mode functions
    // -----------------------------------------------------------------------
    //
    // Three ways to color the segments:
    //   single   — one uniform color (the background's default stroke)
    //   depth    — hue mapped to stack depth. Deeper branches get warmer hues.
    //              This reveals the branching structure visually.
    //   gradient — hue mapped to segment index / total segments, creating a
    //              smooth rainbow along the drawing path.
    // -----------------------------------------------------------------------

    function getSegmentColor(mode, index, totalSegments, depth, maxDepth, bg) {
      const defaults = BACKGROUNDS[bg];
      switch (mode) {
        case 'single':
          return defaults.defaultStroke;
        case 'depth': {
          // Map stack depth to hue: 0 (trunk) = cool blue, max (tips) = warm gold
          const t = maxDepth > 0 ? depth / maxDepth : 0;
          const hue = 220 - t * 180; // 220° (blue) → 40° (gold)
          const sat = 60 + t * 30;
          const lit = bg === 'dark' ? 55 + t * 20 : 30 + t * 15;
          return `hsl(${hue}, ${sat}%, ${lit}%)`;
        }
        case 'gradient': {
          // Map segment index to full hue wheel
          const t = totalSegments > 1 ? index / (totalSegments - 1) : 0;
          const hue = t * 300; // 0° (red) → 300° (magenta)
          const lit = bg === 'dark' ? 60 : 35;
          return `hsl(${hue}, 75%, ${lit}%)`;
        }
        default:
          return defaults.defaultStroke;
      }
    }

    // -----------------------------------------------------------------------
    // Drawing — animated progressive reveal
    // -----------------------------------------------------------------------
    //
    // Instead of drawing all segments at once, we reveal them progressively
    // over ~2 seconds. This creates an animation where you watch the L-system
    // being "drawn" by the turtle, making the construction process visible.
    // The animation also makes it easy to see the order in which segments
    // are traced — trunk first, then branches, then sub-branches.
    // -----------------------------------------------------------------------

    let animId = null;
    let currentSegments = [];
    let currentMaxDepth = 0;

    function cancelAnim() {
      if (animId !== null) {
        cancelAnimationFrame(animId);
        animId = null;
      }
    }

    function drawFrame(segments, maxDepth, upTo, bg, colorMode) {
      const bgDef = BACKGROUNDS[bg];
      ctx.fillStyle = bgDef.fill;
      ctx.fillRect(0, 0, W, H);

      if (segments.length === 0) return;

      // Compute bounding box and scale transform
      const bounds = computeBounds(segments);
      const bw = bounds.xMax - bounds.xMin || 1;
      const bh = bounds.yMax - bounds.yMin || 1;

      // Fit to canvas with padding
      const pad = 40;
      const scaleX = (W - pad * 2) / bw;
      const scaleY = (H - pad * 2) / bh;
      const scale = Math.min(scaleX, scaleY);

      // Center offset
      const cx = (W - bw * scale) / 2 - bounds.xMin * scale;
      const cy = (H - bh * scale) / 2 - bounds.yMin * scale;

      // Line width scales inversely with segment count for readability
      const lw = Math.max(0.3, Math.min(2, 800 / segments.length));
      ctx.lineWidth = lw;
      ctx.lineCap = 'round';

      // Draw segments up to the animation index
      const count = Math.min(upTo, segments.length);

      // For single-color mode, batch into one path for performance
      if (colorMode === 'single') {
        ctx.strokeStyle = bgDef.defaultStroke;
        ctx.beginPath();
        for (let i = 0; i < count; i++) {
          const s = segments[i];
          ctx.moveTo(s.x1 * scale + cx, s.y1 * scale + cy);
          ctx.lineTo(s.x2 * scale + cx, s.y2 * scale + cy);
        }
        ctx.stroke();
      } else {
        // Per-segment color — need individual strokes
        for (let i = 0; i < count; i++) {
          const s = segments[i];
          ctx.strokeStyle = getSegmentColor(
            colorMode, i, segments.length, s.depth, maxDepth, bg
          );
          ctx.beginPath();
          ctx.moveTo(s.x1 * scale + cx, s.y1 * scale + cy);
          ctx.lineTo(s.x2 * scale + cx, s.y2 * scale + cy);
          ctx.stroke();
        }
      }
    }

    function animateDraw() {
      cancelAnim();

      const segments = currentSegments;
      const maxDepth = currentMaxDepth;
      const bg = document.getElementById('ctrl-bg').value;
      const colorMode = document.getElementById('ctrl-color').value;
      const total = segments.length;
      const status = document.getElementById('status');

      if (total === 0) {
        const bgDef = BACKGROUNDS[bg];
        ctx.fillStyle = bgDef.fill;
        ctx.fillRect(0, 0, W, H);
        status.textContent = 'no segments';
        return;
      }

      // Animation duration: ~2 seconds, but at least 1 segment per frame
      // and at most the total count
      const duration = 2000; // ms
      const startTime = performance.now();

      function frame(now) {
        const elapsed = now - startTime;
        const progress = Math.min(1, elapsed / duration);

        // Ease-out for a satisfying draw that slows at the end
        const eased = 1 - Math.pow(1 - progress, 2);
        const upTo = Math.ceil(eased * total);

        drawFrame(segments, maxDepth, upTo, bg, colorMode);

        const pct = Math.round(progress * 100);
        status.textContent = `drawing… ${pct}% · ${upTo.toLocaleString()} / ${total.toLocaleString()} segments`;

        if (progress < 1) {
          animId = requestAnimationFrame(frame);
        } else {
          animId = null;
          status.textContent = `${total.toLocaleString()} segments · done`;
        }
      }

      animId = requestAnimationFrame(frame);
    }

    // -----------------------------------------------------------------------
    // Main: generate L-system and start drawing
    // -----------------------------------------------------------------------

    function generate() {
      const presetKey = document.getElementById('ctrl-preset').value;
      const preset = PRESETS[presetKey];
      const iterations = parseInt(document.getElementById('ctrl-iter').value);
      const angleOffset = parseFloat(document.getElementById('ctrl-angle').value);
      const lengthMul = parseFloat(document.getElementById('ctrl-length').value);
      const status = document.getElementById('status');

      const angle = preset.angle + angleOffset;

      status.textContent = 'rewriting…';

      // Safety: generate the string but bail if it grows too large.
      // We can't estimate accurately because different characters have
      // different rule lengths, so we check during rewriting instead.
      const str = rewrite(preset.axiom, preset.rules, iterations, 5_000_000);
      if (str === null) {
        status.textContent = 'too many iterations — reduce iter count';
        return;
      }

      // Step length: auto-computed to fit nicely, adjustable by the user
      // We use a base of 4 pixels, which the auto-scaling will adjust anyway
      const stepLen = 4 * lengthMul;

      status.textContent = 'interpreting…';
      const { segments, maxDepth } = interpretToSegments(str, angle, stepLen);
      currentSegments = segments;
      currentMaxDepth = maxDepth;

      animateDraw();
    }

    // -----------------------------------------------------------------------
    // Controls
    // -----------------------------------------------------------------------

    const presetSelect = document.getElementById('ctrl-preset');
    const iterSlider = document.getElementById('ctrl-iter');
    const iterVal = document.getElementById('val-iter');
    const angleSlider = document.getElementById('ctrl-angle');
    const angleVal = document.getElementById('val-angle');
    const lengthSlider = document.getElementById('ctrl-length');
    const lengthVal = document.getElementById('val-length');

    // When preset changes, reset iterations and angle to preset defaults
    presetSelect.addEventListener('change', () => {
      const preset = PRESETS[presetSelect.value];
      iterSlider.value = preset.iter;
      iterVal.textContent = preset.iter;
      angleSlider.value = 0;
      angleVal.textContent = '0°';
      lengthSlider.value = 1;
      lengthVal.textContent = '1×';
      generate();
    });

    iterSlider.addEventListener('input', () => {
      iterVal.textContent = iterSlider.value;
      generate();
    });

    angleSlider.addEventListener('input', () => {
      const v = parseFloat(angleSlider.value);
      angleVal.textContent = (v >= 0 ? '+' : '') + v + '°';
      const wide = angleVal.textContent.length >= 5;
      angleVal.classList.toggle('bulge', wide);
      generate();
    });

    lengthSlider.addEventListener('input', () => {
      lengthVal.textContent = parseFloat(lengthSlider.value).toFixed(1) + '×';
      generate();
    });

    document.getElementById('ctrl-color').addEventListener('change', () => {
      // Redraw immediately without re-generating (just re-animate)
      animateDraw();
    });

    document.getElementById('ctrl-bg').addEventListener('change', () => {
      animateDraw();
    });

    document.getElementById('btn-save').addEventListener('click', () => {
      saveCanvasPNG(canvas, `l-system-${presetSelect.value}.png`);
    });

    document.getElementById('toggle-ui').addEventListener('click', () => {
      document.getElementById('controls').classList.toggle('hidden');
    });

    window.addEventListener('resize', () => {
      resize();
      // Redraw at current state without re-animating
      if (currentSegments.length > 0) {
        const bg = document.getElementById('ctrl-bg').value;
        const colorMode = document.getElementById('ctrl-color').value;
        drawFrame(currentSegments, currentMaxDepth, currentSegments.length, bg, colorMode);
      }
    });

    // -----------------------------------------------------------------------
    // Go — wait for layout to settle so the container has real dimensions
    // -----------------------------------------------------------------------
    function boot() {
      resize();
      if (W > 0 && H > 0) {
        generate();
      } else {
        requestAnimationFrame(boot);
      }
    }
    requestAnimationFrame(boot);
  </script>
</body>
</html>
